s, and you can perform the following operations until the array is empty:\n\nIf the first element has the smallest value, remove it\nOtherwise, put the first element at the end of the array.\n\nReturn an integer denoting the number of operations it takes to make nums empty.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [3,4,-1]\nOutput: 5\n\n\n\n\nOperation\nArray\n\n\n\n\n1\n[4, -1, 3]\n\n\n2\n[-1, 3, 4]\n\n\n3\n[3, 4]\n\n\n4\n[4]\n\n\n5\n[]\n\n\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,4,3]\nOutput: 5\n\n\n\n\nOperation\nArray\n\n\n\n\n1\n[2, 4, 3]\n\n\n2\n[4, 3]\n\n\n3\n[3, 4]\n\n\n4\n[4]\n\n\n5\n[]\n\n\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,3]\nOutput: 3\n\n\n\n\nOperation\nArray\n\n\n\n\n1\n[2, 3]\n\n\n2\n[3]\n\n\n3\n[]\n\n\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 105\n-109 <= nums[i] <= 109\nAll values in nums are distinct.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def countOperationsToEmptyArray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom sortedcontainers import SortedList\nfrom itertools import pairwise\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def countOperationsToEmptyArray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        pos = {x: i for i, x in enumerate(nums)}\n        nums.sort()\n        sl = SortedList()\n        ans = pos[nums[0]] + 1\n        n = len(nums)\n        for k, (a, b) in enumerate(pairwise(nums)):\n            i, j = pos[a], pos[b]\n            d = j - i - sl.bisect(j) + sl.bisect(i)\n            ans += d + (n - k) * int(i > j)\n            sl.add(i)\n        return ans\n```\n\nThis solution uses a `SortedList` to keep track of the positions of the elements that have already been considered. It calculates the number of operations needed to remove each element by determining how many elements have been shifted due to previous removals. The `pairwise` function from the `itertools` module is used to iterate over pairs of consecutive elements in the sorted list, and the `bisect` method of `SortedList` is used to efficiently find the number of elements that have been shifted.", "estimated_date": 1682208000000}